1
00:00:01,001 --> 00:00:02,641
Previously on
"The Good Doctor"...

2
00:00:02,670 --> 00:00:05,470
Dr. Coyle --
He's a little too friendly.

3
00:00:05,506 --> 00:00:06,536
I'm sure he's just trying
to establish a rapport.

4
00:00:06,574 --> 00:00:08,184
Coyle:
I give great massages.

5
00:00:08,209 --> 00:00:09,509
And I'll make a killer omelet
in the morning.

6
00:00:09,543 --> 00:00:10,783
That's really
inappropriate.

7
00:00:10,811 --> 00:00:12,451
I said no.

8
00:00:12,480 --> 00:00:13,380
You're approaching
insubordination.

9
00:00:13,414 --> 00:00:15,484
Jared: You have to file
a complaint with HR.

10
00:00:15,516 --> 00:00:18,516
They will shift the blame
onto me. Like you did.

11
00:00:19,720 --> 00:00:20,520
I've just been fired

12
00:00:20,554 --> 00:00:21,564
for physically assaulting
an employee.

13
00:00:21,589 --> 00:00:23,619
So, why do I need to quit my job
to have a family?

14
00:00:23,657 --> 00:00:26,057
Agreed. She can be
a great lawyer and a great mom.

15
00:00:26,094 --> 00:00:27,304
I don't want to have kids.

16
00:00:27,328 --> 00:00:29,298
Shaun:
I don't need a therapist.

17
00:00:29,330 --> 00:00:31,230
I want to make
my own decisions.

18
00:00:31,265 --> 00:00:32,225
I am done talking.

19
00:00:32,266 --> 00:00:33,366
Now let's go.
No. N-No.

20
00:00:33,401 --> 00:00:34,401
I don't want help!

21
00:00:34,435 --> 00:00:35,295
Melissa:
Where would he go?

22
00:00:35,336 --> 00:00:36,736
Is there a place
he likes to hang out?

23
00:00:36,770 --> 00:00:38,140
I mean, he's not
at the hospital.

24
00:00:38,172 --> 00:00:39,472
And there used to be
a picture here.

25
00:00:39,507 --> 00:00:41,537
It means
he's not coming back.

26
00:00:42,276 --> 00:00:44,706
[ Knock on door ]

27
00:00:44,745 --> 00:00:46,345
Hi. Good morning.

28
00:00:46,380 --> 00:00:48,120
I'm Aaron Glassman.
Dr. Glassman.

29
00:00:48,149 --> 00:00:49,449
I work with Shaun.

30
00:00:49,483 --> 00:00:51,323
Hi. Nice to meet you.

31
00:00:51,352 --> 00:00:53,552
It's nice to meet you, too.
May I speak with him, please?

32
00:00:53,587 --> 00:00:56,357
Uh, Shaun isn't here.

33
00:00:56,390 --> 00:01:01,530
I know you've been helping
Shaun, and I appreciate that,

34
00:01:01,562 --> 00:01:03,702
but I really need
to speak with him immediately.

35
00:01:03,731 --> 00:01:07,141
I'll definitely let him know
when I see him next.

36
00:01:07,835 --> 00:01:09,235
I'm -- I'm sorry.

37
00:01:09,270 --> 00:01:10,300
What the hell
are you doing?

38
00:01:10,338 --> 00:01:11,568
Shaun,
I know you're in here.

39
00:01:11,605 --> 00:01:14,205
I just --
I just want to talk, please.

40
00:01:14,242 --> 00:01:15,482
You are way out of line.

41
00:01:15,509 --> 00:01:17,809
Shaun, you have
responsibilities.

42
00:01:17,845 --> 00:01:18,945
We've got to
sort this out.

43
00:01:18,979 --> 00:01:21,149
You have five seconds
to get the hell out of here...

44
00:01:21,182 --> 00:01:22,382
-Shaun.
-...or I'm calling the police.

45
00:01:22,416 --> 00:01:23,776
-Shaun, I just --
-What are --

46
00:01:23,817 --> 00:01:26,347
I just want to...

47
00:01:26,387 --> 00:01:29,217
-Five...
-Shaun.

48
00:01:29,257 --> 00:01:30,717
Shaun,
she's calling the police.

49
00:01:30,758 --> 00:01:32,288
-...four...
-Is that what you want?

50
00:01:32,326 --> 00:01:33,886
Lea: ...three...

51
00:01:33,927 --> 00:01:35,297
...two...
-Okay, okay.

52
00:01:35,329 --> 00:01:36,759
-...one.
-Okay, okay, I'm leaving.

53
00:01:36,797 --> 00:01:40,127
It's just that
Shaun has a-a tendency

54
00:01:40,168 --> 00:01:41,298
to run away
from conflict.

55
00:01:41,335 --> 00:01:43,495
And in Casper
and medical school,

56
00:01:43,537 --> 00:01:45,907
people will give you
a little bit of slack, but it --

57
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:47,709
now he's in a very
hard-to-get job

58
00:01:47,741 --> 00:01:49,581
in a very competitive
environment

59
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:51,880
where people do not give you
a second chance.

60
00:01:51,912 --> 00:01:56,552
Still, not cool.

61
00:02:00,254 --> 00:02:02,864
If you speak with him
[clears throat]

62
00:02:02,890 --> 00:02:04,360
will you call me,
please?

63
00:02:04,392 --> 00:02:06,492
Out.

64
00:02:08,496 --> 00:02:10,396
Yeah.

65
00:02:10,431 --> 00:02:13,431
[ Door opens, closes ]

66
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:15,167
[ Sighs ]

67
00:02:19,307 --> 00:02:21,277
[ Lea sighs ]

68
00:02:21,309 --> 00:02:23,909
So, what's your plan now?

69
00:02:26,414 --> 00:02:29,254
I don't know.

70
00:02:29,283 --> 00:02:32,223
-- Captions by VITAC --

71
00:02:32,253 --> 00:02:39,233
**

72
00:02:39,260 --> 00:02:42,200
I gotta say, he seems like
a nebby, old jerk.

73
00:02:42,230 --> 00:02:43,200
And a bully.

74
00:02:43,231 --> 00:02:44,631
What's "nebby"?

75
00:02:44,665 --> 00:02:46,965
Nosey.
It's a Pittsburgh thing.

76
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:48,640
I mean,
you're a grown man.

77
00:02:48,669 --> 00:02:50,899
If you don't want to talk to
him, it's none of his business.

78
00:02:50,938 --> 00:02:54,978
San Jose is too big.

79
00:02:55,008 --> 00:02:57,578
I get not liking San Jose.

80
00:02:57,611 --> 00:02:59,311
I'm not the biggest fan myself,
but --

81
00:02:59,347 --> 00:03:01,677
I don't want to see
a therapist.

82
00:03:01,715 --> 00:03:03,475
So don't.

83
00:03:05,719 --> 00:03:08,459
I should go back to Casper.

84
00:03:08,489 --> 00:03:09,789
I have a rule.

85
00:03:09,823 --> 00:03:13,293
Never make an important
decision while you are angry,

86
00:03:13,327 --> 00:03:17,267
upset, high, or right before
or after having sex.

87
00:03:17,298 --> 00:03:19,798
Okay, you are overworked,
stressed out,

88
00:03:19,833 --> 00:03:20,833
and pissed off
at your boss.

89
00:03:20,868 --> 00:03:23,898
Now is not the time
to be making a big decision.

90
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:27,437
You need to take a break,
clear your head.

91
00:03:27,475 --> 00:03:28,875
You need a vacation.

92
00:03:28,909 --> 00:03:32,679
I have to work five more months
before I earn a vacation.

93
00:03:32,713 --> 00:03:34,783
So call in sick.

94
00:03:34,815 --> 00:03:36,615
I'm not sick.

95
00:03:36,650 --> 00:03:38,790
[ Sighs ]
You're so adorable.

96
00:03:38,819 --> 00:03:41,619
You don't have to be sick
to call in sick.

97
00:03:41,655 --> 00:03:44,285
Ah, I have so much
to teach you, Grasshopper.

98
00:03:44,325 --> 00:03:47,425
And I'm gonna start with
a good, old-fashioned road trip.

99
00:03:47,461 --> 00:03:49,031
It's the perfect way
to get your mojo back.

100
00:03:49,062 --> 00:03:51,472
And when we return, you're
gonna know exactly what to do

101
00:03:51,499 --> 00:03:55,339
about San Jose, therapy,
and Glassy the Grouch.

102
00:03:55,369 --> 00:03:56,299
And all you have to do

103
00:03:56,337 --> 00:03:58,837
to attain this superior wisdom
and knowledge

104
00:03:58,872 --> 00:04:05,952
is to call...in...sick.

105
00:04:09,950 --> 00:04:12,550
Okay. Okay. I will.

106
00:04:12,586 --> 00:04:15,656
**

107
00:04:15,689 --> 00:04:18,059
Dr. Melendez.
Got a case for you.

108
00:04:18,091 --> 00:04:19,161
My schedule's
pretty packed today.

109
00:04:19,192 --> 00:04:22,502
It's a patient of mine.
She needs a kidney transplant.

110
00:04:22,530 --> 00:04:24,470
You have a donor?

111
00:04:24,498 --> 00:04:26,798
Her identical twin --
a perfect DNA match.

112
00:04:26,834 --> 00:04:27,904
Why is she
a patient of yours?

113
00:04:27,935 --> 00:04:30,735
I put balloon tissue expanders
under both girls' scalps

114
00:04:30,771 --> 00:04:32,871
to prepare them
for the separation surgery.

115
00:04:32,906 --> 00:04:34,406
Separation surgery?

116
00:04:34,442 --> 00:04:39,382
**

117
00:04:39,413 --> 00:04:42,753
It's in six months, after they
recover from the transplant.

118
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:44,053
Of course,
if you're too busy...

119
00:04:44,084 --> 00:04:46,554
No. I'm in.

120
00:04:48,956 --> 00:04:51,656
Where's Murphy?
-He's not here yet.

121
00:04:51,692 --> 00:04:54,432
Wrong day to be late.
We're already shorthanded.

122
00:04:55,128 --> 00:04:57,798
Actually, I wanted
to talk to you about that.
I did not fire Kalu.

123
00:04:57,831 --> 00:05:00,401
And if you have a problem
with it, talk to Andrews.

124
00:05:00,434 --> 00:05:03,804
Although, if you want my advice,
don't have a problem with it.

125
00:05:04,738 --> 00:05:06,908
Andrews is waiting
to brief us on a new case.

126
00:05:06,940 --> 00:05:10,110
It's a kidney transplant
on craniopagus twins.

127
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:11,883
Conjoined?

128
00:05:11,912 --> 00:05:13,012
They're connected
at the skull.

129
00:05:13,046 --> 00:05:16,446
Their entire renal-vascular
systems are interdependent.

130
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:17,920
Cool.

131
00:05:17,951 --> 00:05:20,421
Hey. Have either of you
talked to Shaun?

132
00:05:20,454 --> 00:05:23,564
-No.
-No, which isn't unusual.

133
00:05:23,591 --> 00:05:24,561
Is anything wrong?

134
00:05:24,592 --> 00:05:28,002
No, no, not with Shaun.
It's a family emergency.

135
00:05:28,028 --> 00:05:30,528
He's gonna be out
for a few days.
He's supposed to
get approval

136
00:05:30,564 --> 00:05:32,704
for any personal days
from his attending.

137
00:05:32,733 --> 00:05:34,103
Right, which is why
I'm checking in.

138
00:05:34,134 --> 00:05:37,674
I think he thought it was enough
just to notify me.

139
00:05:38,572 --> 00:05:44,042
**

140
00:05:44,077 --> 00:05:49,717
**

141
00:05:49,750 --> 00:05:50,820
You call in sick?

142
00:05:53,454 --> 00:05:55,494
I'm ready to go.

143
00:05:55,523 --> 00:05:57,393
[ Zipper zips ]

144
00:05:57,425 --> 00:05:59,125
No, you're not.

145
00:06:03,964 --> 00:06:06,734
You're gonna need more than
a family photo and a toothbrush.

146
00:06:06,767 --> 00:06:07,767
Go pack.

147
00:06:07,801 --> 00:06:08,941
Uh, where are we going?

148
00:06:08,969 --> 00:06:10,499
Wherever the car takes us.

149
00:06:10,538 --> 00:06:11,568
I don't like the beach.

150
00:06:11,605 --> 00:06:13,935
Okay,
I will let the car know.

151
00:06:15,175 --> 00:06:17,035
Even with
your cardiovascular issues,

152
00:06:17,077 --> 00:06:19,807
a kidney transplant
is a relatively safe procedure,

153
00:06:19,847 --> 00:06:21,717
especially since,
with identical twins,

154
00:06:21,749 --> 00:06:23,749
there's no chance
for organ rejection.

155
00:06:23,784 --> 00:06:25,794
Just make sure you keep straight
which one's which.

156
00:06:25,819 --> 00:06:29,519
The charming, pretty one
has the good kidneys.

157
00:06:29,557 --> 00:06:32,127
Don't worry.
We always triple confirm.

158
00:06:32,159 --> 00:06:34,629
And we put everything
in writing.

159
00:06:34,662 --> 00:06:36,462
And you're both charming
and pretty.

160
00:06:36,497 --> 00:06:38,127
-Mm-hmm.
-It was a joke, Mom.

161
00:06:38,165 --> 00:06:39,925
Glenda: And smart.

162
00:06:39,967 --> 00:06:41,497
They're gonna be Ivy Leaguers
in the fall.

163
00:06:41,535 --> 00:06:43,735
Yale and Harvard.
-Wow.

164
00:06:43,771 --> 00:06:45,711
Mom, you don't have to tell
everyone you meet

165
00:06:45,739 --> 00:06:48,009
where we're going to college.
-Yes, I do.

166
00:06:48,041 --> 00:06:50,541
That's awesome.
Congratulations.

167
00:06:50,578 --> 00:06:53,448
So, who's going where?

168
00:06:53,481 --> 00:06:55,551
What do you think?
She's totally obnoxious

169
00:06:55,583 --> 00:06:57,053
and thinks she's way funnier
than she is.

170
00:06:57,084 --> 00:07:00,054
-Definitely Harvard.
-Mm-hmm.

171
00:07:00,087 --> 00:07:02,457
Hey, don't make me start
mocking your tattoo.

172
00:07:02,490 --> 00:07:05,060
[ Both laugh ]

173
00:07:07,528 --> 00:07:09,228
I thought you would have
your entire apartment

174
00:07:09,262 --> 00:07:10,262
strapped to your back.

175
00:07:10,297 --> 00:07:13,567
It takes me a long time
to pack.
That's good.

176
00:07:13,601 --> 00:07:16,041
An anal-retentive packer
is the exact type of person

177
00:07:16,069 --> 00:07:17,539
I'd want operating
on me.

178
00:07:17,571 --> 00:07:19,841
Lea, this --
this is your car.

179
00:07:19,873 --> 00:07:21,943
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
We're gonna take my other one.

180
00:07:21,975 --> 00:07:25,805
Okay.
What do you do at work?

181
00:07:25,846 --> 00:07:28,576
Do you really care what I do,
or do you just want to know

182
00:07:28,616 --> 00:07:31,486
how someone with such a crappy
apartment can afford two cars?

183
00:07:31,519 --> 00:07:35,589
I just want to know
how you can afford two cars.

184
00:07:35,623 --> 00:07:37,663
Hmm.

185
00:07:37,691 --> 00:07:38,931
Yeah, I can't.

186
00:07:38,959 --> 00:07:41,159
Uh, my Grandpa Rod died
last year,

187
00:07:41,194 --> 00:07:44,874
and he left me
his most prized possession.

188
00:07:44,898 --> 00:07:46,898
[ Chuckles ]

189
00:07:46,934 --> 00:07:50,804
It's
the S-Striped Tomato.

190
00:07:50,838 --> 00:07:52,168
Oh, my God.
You like "Starsky & Hutch"?

191
00:07:52,205 --> 00:07:53,905
It's okay.

192
00:07:53,941 --> 00:07:57,081
A meticulous packer
and a "Starsky & Hutch" fan.

193
00:07:57,110 --> 00:07:58,650
Grandpa Rod
would have loved you.

194
00:07:58,679 --> 00:08:05,989
**

195
00:08:06,019 --> 00:08:09,859
Okay. This is it.
The road.

196
00:08:09,890 --> 00:08:11,590
You sure
you want to do this?

197
00:08:11,625 --> 00:08:15,095
Speak now
or forever hold your peace.

198
00:08:15,763 --> 00:08:17,703
I'm sure.

199
00:08:18,832 --> 00:08:20,632
Let's go, Lea.

200
00:08:20,668 --> 00:08:21,668
[ Tires squeal ]

201
00:08:21,702 --> 00:08:22,872
Here we go!
[ Laughs ]

202
00:08:22,903 --> 00:08:28,643
**

203
00:08:33,113 --> 00:08:38,123
[ Knock on door ]
I hear Murphy's AWOL.

204
00:08:38,151 --> 00:08:40,551
He's taking
a few personal days.

205
00:08:40,588 --> 00:08:41,818
Unapproved personal days.

206
00:08:41,855 --> 00:08:42,955
I approved them.

207
00:08:42,990 --> 00:08:44,160
It's not your job
to approve them.

208
00:08:44,191 --> 00:08:47,291
Or to say you approved them
to cover up the fact

209
00:08:47,327 --> 00:08:50,327
that Murphy's frequent tardiness
has escalated to absences.

210
00:08:50,363 --> 00:08:53,973
What do you want me to do,
take a polygraph?

211
00:08:54,001 --> 00:08:56,071
How about we jump into
enhanced interrogation?

212
00:08:56,103 --> 00:08:59,643
Here, how about this?
Do you want me to turn this on?

213
00:08:59,673 --> 00:09:02,183
When the board was reconsidering
your hiring of Murphy,

214
00:09:02,209 --> 00:09:06,749
you assured us that if he was
anything less than excellent,

215
00:09:06,780 --> 00:09:08,650
he'd be dismissed
and you would resign.

216
00:09:08,682 --> 00:09:09,882
I trust
you remember that.

217
00:09:09,917 --> 00:09:13,147
I wouldn't have your movers
pack up your office just yet.

218
00:09:13,186 --> 00:09:15,156
You can't protect Murphy
forever.

219
00:09:15,188 --> 00:09:20,288
At some point, he needs
to succeed or fail on his own.

220
00:09:20,327 --> 00:09:24,157
**

221
00:09:24,197 --> 00:09:27,097
J.L.: Okay, that's three hours
on the warm ischemia clock

222
00:09:27,134 --> 00:09:29,204
of the transplanted kidney.

223
00:09:29,236 --> 00:09:32,266
Melendez: The ureter is attached
to the bladder.

224
00:09:32,305 --> 00:09:36,175
How's the kidney's placement
in the iliac fossa?

225
00:09:37,144 --> 00:09:39,254
No kinking or twisting
of the renal vessel.

226
00:09:39,279 --> 00:09:41,619
Good.

227
00:09:42,382 --> 00:09:44,722
You ready to close?

228
00:09:45,719 --> 00:09:47,689
Yes.

229
00:09:48,421 --> 00:09:52,131
Your best bet is a continuous
suture along the fascial layer.

230
00:09:52,159 --> 00:09:54,729
Suture.

231
00:09:56,096 --> 00:09:57,196
[ Alarm beeping ]

232
00:09:57,230 --> 00:09:59,330
Donor's pressure's
dropping.

233
00:09:59,366 --> 00:10:00,766
Okay, up the oxygen.

234
00:10:00,801 --> 00:10:02,101
Jenny must be bleeding
internally.

235
00:10:02,135 --> 00:10:03,265
We're gonna have to
open her back up.

236
00:10:03,303 --> 00:10:05,013
Staple remover.

237
00:10:05,038 --> 00:10:11,208
**

238
00:10:12,079 --> 00:10:14,749
I like trees.

239
00:10:14,782 --> 00:10:16,752
Yeah?
What else do you like?

240
00:10:16,784 --> 00:10:18,424
Besides reading
medical journals

241
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:21,351
and watching reruns
of old cop shows?

242
00:10:21,388 --> 00:10:23,688
[ Chuckles ]
-I like you.

243
00:10:23,724 --> 00:10:25,994
Well, who wouldn't?
I'm very likeable.

244
00:10:26,026 --> 00:10:28,726
Why don't you like
San Jose?

245
00:10:28,762 --> 00:10:31,102
Everyone's
so competitive here.

246
00:10:31,131 --> 00:10:34,001
You know, if you didn't make
a million by 30,

247
00:10:34,034 --> 00:10:35,074
you're a total loser.

248
00:10:35,102 --> 00:10:37,372
I don't need $1 million.

249
00:10:37,404 --> 00:10:40,444
I don't even think
I need $90,000, but...

250
00:10:40,473 --> 00:10:42,883
You know what we both need
are some tunes.

251
00:10:42,910 --> 00:10:44,280
What's your preferred
driving music?

252
00:10:44,311 --> 00:10:47,411
M-Music -- No. N--
I don't like music. No. No.

253
00:10:47,447 --> 00:10:50,877
What? No, no.
Not okay.

254
00:10:50,918 --> 00:10:53,118
Okay, I will give you a pass
on not liking the beach

255
00:10:53,153 --> 00:10:54,253
because you're cute

256
00:10:54,287 --> 00:10:56,787
and I might need you to do
brain surgery on me someday,

257
00:10:56,824 --> 00:10:59,694
but not liking music --
unacceptable.

258
00:10:59,727 --> 00:11:00,687
I won't have it.

259
00:11:00,728 --> 00:11:02,428
Are you being sarcastic?

260
00:11:02,462 --> 00:11:05,172
No. I'm being...

261
00:11:05,198 --> 00:11:07,998
I actually don't know the word
for it, but my point stands.

262
00:11:08,035 --> 00:11:09,995
Music is amazing.

263
00:11:10,037 --> 00:11:12,207
You know, I remember
every important thing

264
00:11:12,239 --> 00:11:13,309
that has ever happened
to me

265
00:11:13,340 --> 00:11:17,240
based on what song
I was listening to at the time.

266
00:11:17,277 --> 00:11:19,877
I remember smells.

267
00:11:19,913 --> 00:11:23,453
Like our parking garage
smells like fabric softener,

268
00:11:23,483 --> 00:11:26,993
and when my brother died,
it smelled like burnt food.

269
00:11:27,487 --> 00:11:31,727
Oh, my God. I'm so sorry.
I had no idea.

270
00:11:31,759 --> 00:11:36,859
How did he, um...
if you don't mind me asking?

271
00:11:37,197 --> 00:11:40,097
My father was mean.

272
00:11:40,133 --> 00:11:44,813
He killed my pet, so my brother
and I, we ran away.

273
00:11:44,838 --> 00:11:46,838
Then he fell off a train
we were playing on,

274
00:11:46,874 --> 00:11:48,844
hit his head, and died.

275
00:11:50,477 --> 00:11:54,407
I never went back home.

276
00:11:54,447 --> 00:11:58,947
Dr. Glassman has watched out
for me ever since.

277
00:11:59,887 --> 00:12:05,987
Okay, so, maybe he's not
that much of a nebby jerk.

278
00:12:07,961 --> 00:12:11,261
What are you smelling
right now?

279
00:12:12,265 --> 00:12:14,935
Pine trees.

280
00:12:16,069 --> 00:12:18,539
Mm.
I'm never gonna forget

281
00:12:18,571 --> 00:12:20,471
that when you told me
about your brother and your dad,

282
00:12:20,507 --> 00:12:22,877
it smelled
like pine trees.

283
00:12:22,910 --> 00:12:25,010
But I don't want you
to ever forget

284
00:12:25,045 --> 00:12:27,915
that right after you told me,
we were listening to...

285
00:12:27,948 --> 00:12:29,178
[ Heavy metal blares ]

286
00:12:29,216 --> 00:12:31,416
Ouch. No.
Do not remember that.

287
00:12:31,451 --> 00:12:33,151
[ Singing in Spanish ]
Or that.

288
00:12:33,186 --> 00:12:34,486
No, thank you.

289
00:12:34,521 --> 00:12:37,061
* ...that again, I say it -- *
Nope. Not feeling it.

290
00:12:37,090 --> 00:12:40,930
* ...the satellites
in the fuse box, too *
Ooh, so good.

291
00:12:40,961 --> 00:12:44,561
* Our sharp teeth
are the only light *
This is the one
you will not forget.

292
00:12:44,597 --> 00:12:45,727
Do not forget this.

293
00:12:45,765 --> 00:12:47,795
* I drank the whole moon dry *
* Moon dry

294
00:12:47,835 --> 00:12:49,435
* 'Cause all my friends
are metalheads *

295
00:12:49,469 --> 00:12:51,199
* Swear they'd never
catch us dead *

296
00:12:51,238 --> 00:12:54,368
* Split up
when the police come *

297
00:12:54,407 --> 00:12:58,207
* Yeah, running
used to get me high, high *

298
00:12:58,245 --> 00:13:03,115
* Now I only feel tired *

299
00:13:03,150 --> 00:13:06,820
**

300
00:13:06,854 --> 00:13:08,964
Jenny had a post-op
renal-vein rupture.

301
00:13:08,989 --> 00:13:11,459
We were able to repair it
before she lost too much blood.

302
00:13:11,491 --> 00:13:12,931
Both your vitals
are stable now,

303
00:13:12,960 --> 00:13:14,860
and Katie's new kidney
is functioning well.

304
00:13:14,895 --> 00:13:16,255
Thank God.

305
00:13:16,296 --> 00:13:19,466
Will her ruptured vein
have any effect on our
separation surgery?

306
00:13:19,499 --> 00:13:20,599
It better not.

307
00:13:20,633 --> 00:13:22,343
Katie, I love you,
but if I have to spend

308
00:13:22,369 --> 00:13:23,839
one minute more
than I have to

309
00:13:23,871 --> 00:13:26,271
watching you practicing
some Mozart song --

310
00:13:26,306 --> 00:13:29,036
They're not songs.
They're concertos.
Pbht!

311
00:13:29,076 --> 00:13:32,146
Don't worry.
Six months is still the plan.

312
00:13:32,179 --> 00:13:35,019
[ Sighs ]

313
00:13:41,588 --> 00:13:44,188
[ Door closes ]

314
00:13:44,224 --> 00:13:45,234
[ Sighs ]

315
00:13:45,258 --> 00:13:48,398
Look, what I did
was incredibly unprofessional

316
00:13:48,428 --> 00:13:52,028
and just...inexcusable.

317
00:13:52,065 --> 00:13:55,095
But I'm guessing
you're gonna give one anyway.

318
00:13:55,135 --> 00:13:56,635
No.

319
00:13:56,669 --> 00:14:01,169
No, just an explanation
and a, uh...request.

320
00:14:02,342 --> 00:14:04,012
It could help me
to convince Andrews

321
00:14:04,044 --> 00:14:05,284
I deserve
a second chance.

322
00:14:05,312 --> 00:14:09,482
Okay.
Let's hear the explanation.

323
00:14:09,950 --> 00:14:13,150
Dr. Browne and I are...
seeing each other.

324
00:14:13,186 --> 00:14:15,956
Look, if you could just
put yourself in my shoes.

325
00:14:15,989 --> 00:14:18,989
A woman I care about tells me
a guy harassed her,

326
00:14:19,026 --> 00:14:20,556
and, even worse,
she tells me it's my fault

327
00:14:20,593 --> 00:14:23,663
because I was too --
too stupidly insensitive

328
00:14:23,696 --> 00:14:25,166
to understand
what she was going through.

329
00:14:25,198 --> 00:14:28,568
I felt like crap.

330
00:14:28,601 --> 00:14:34,011
And like an idiot,
I...tried to make it up to her.

331
00:14:36,944 --> 00:14:40,354
All I'm asking for
is just a little understanding.

332
00:14:41,114 --> 00:14:42,284
Wouldn't you have done
the same thing?

333
00:14:42,315 --> 00:14:47,955
**

334
00:14:47,988 --> 00:14:50,058
Not my problem.

335
00:14:53,326 --> 00:14:54,156
Claire: Yeah?

336
00:14:54,194 --> 00:14:56,334
Jenny's bradycardic
and hypotensive.

337
00:14:56,363 --> 00:14:58,233
-What's happening?
-She was fine a minute ago.

338
00:14:58,265 --> 00:15:00,365
We were talking, then
she started to have
trouble breathing.

339
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:03,570
[ Monitor beeping ]

340
00:15:04,571 --> 00:15:06,341
Jenny's heart
is failing.

341
00:15:07,740 --> 00:15:08,710
No pulse.

342
00:15:08,741 --> 00:15:10,541
She's in V-tach.
Grab the cart, page Melendez.

343
00:15:10,577 --> 00:15:13,907
[ Alarm beeping rapidly ]

344
00:15:21,454 --> 00:15:22,464
Jenny's stable.

345
00:15:23,490 --> 00:15:24,720
I have her on beta blockers
and vasodilators,

346
00:15:24,757 --> 00:15:26,287
but it's not
gonna be enough.

347
00:15:26,326 --> 00:15:27,526
Renal-vein rupture
must have caused

348
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:29,400
her already weak heart
to deteriorate.

349
00:15:29,429 --> 00:15:32,069
She's in end-stage failure.
I'll get her
on the transplant registry.

350
00:15:32,099 --> 00:15:34,729
What are we talking?
Months? Weeks?
Days.

351
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:37,497
We're not gonna find
a donor heart in a few days.

352
00:15:40,273 --> 00:15:43,683
We could disconnect her
from the other body

353
00:15:43,710 --> 00:15:46,680
her heart is partially
oxygenating the blood for.

354
00:15:48,115 --> 00:15:49,345
I was already pushing
the envelope

355
00:15:49,382 --> 00:15:50,522
to do
the separation surgery

356
00:15:50,550 --> 00:15:52,490
six months
after a kidney transplant.

357
00:15:52,519 --> 00:15:55,159
Do you really think they could
handle it one day after?

358
00:15:56,023 --> 00:15:58,733
It may be our only choice.

359
00:16:01,361 --> 00:16:02,331
Yeah.

360
00:16:02,362 --> 00:16:05,002
[ Cellphone chimes ]

361
00:16:06,366 --> 00:16:08,596
His calls are an even bigger
buzzkill than this rain

362
00:16:08,635 --> 00:16:11,035
and defeating the whole purpose
of this trip.

363
00:16:11,071 --> 00:16:12,571
Okay.

364
00:16:12,605 --> 00:16:17,675
Residents are not supposed to
turn off their phones.

365
00:16:17,710 --> 00:16:19,280
How about we make a deal?

366
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:23,222
If you turn off your phone,
I'll let you drive.

367
00:16:23,250 --> 00:16:26,620
I don't have
a driver's license.
I know.

368
00:16:26,653 --> 00:16:29,663
I've always wanted
to learn to drive.
I know.

369
00:16:29,689 --> 00:16:33,029
Dr. Glassman --
he never wanted me to.
I know.

370
00:16:33,060 --> 00:16:34,130
Actually,
I didn't know that,

371
00:16:34,161 --> 00:16:37,101
but that definitely sounds
like Glassy.

372
00:16:39,132 --> 00:16:40,072
Okay.

373
00:16:40,100 --> 00:16:42,040
Yeah? [ Giggles ]

374
00:16:42,069 --> 00:16:47,809
**

375
00:16:47,840 --> 00:16:49,380
You're doing awesome.

376
00:16:49,409 --> 00:16:52,149
You're a natural.

377
00:16:52,179 --> 00:16:53,479
Thank you.

378
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:56,083
I think so, too.

379
00:16:56,816 --> 00:16:59,146
Blinker.

380
00:16:59,186 --> 00:17:03,256
All right,
now make this left turn.

381
00:17:03,290 --> 00:17:04,690
Okay,
don't circle this time.

382
00:17:04,724 --> 00:17:08,164
Just keep going straight.

383
00:17:10,197 --> 00:17:12,567
[ Brakes squeal ]
What are you stopping for?

384
00:17:12,599 --> 00:17:15,369
You want me
to go out on the street?

385
00:17:15,768 --> 00:17:19,368
It's where the car
wants to go.

386
00:17:19,406 --> 00:17:21,166
Come on.

387
00:17:21,208 --> 00:17:23,838
What's the worst thing
that could happen?

388
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:28,646
I could run over someone
and kill them.

389
00:17:28,681 --> 00:17:31,181
You have autism.
You're not blind.

390
00:17:31,218 --> 00:17:32,518
And I'll be right here
with you.

391
00:17:32,552 --> 00:17:34,592
Mm-hmm.

392
00:17:34,621 --> 00:17:39,561
**

393
00:17:39,592 --> 00:17:42,732
Half Dome, here we come.

394
00:17:42,762 --> 00:17:43,862
Can I turn on the radio?

395
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:46,496
-No! No, thank you.
-Okay, okay.

396
00:17:46,533 --> 00:17:52,273
**

397
00:17:52,305 --> 00:17:57,835
**

398
00:17:57,877 --> 00:17:59,307
Nice.

399
00:17:59,346 --> 00:18:04,216
**

400
00:18:04,251 --> 00:18:06,691
We believe moving up
the separation surgery

401
00:18:06,719 --> 00:18:08,659
will lighten the load
on Jenny's heart,

402
00:18:08,688 --> 00:18:10,258
maybe allow it
to recover a bit

403
00:18:10,290 --> 00:18:12,530
so a transplant won't even
be necessary in the future.

404
00:18:12,559 --> 00:18:14,559
It is higher risk
for Katie now,

405
00:18:14,594 --> 00:18:16,864
given that her new kidney
is still not fully functional.

406
00:18:16,896 --> 00:18:19,526
What do you think
we should do?

407
00:18:19,566 --> 00:18:21,866
It's your bodies.
Your decision.

408
00:18:21,901 --> 00:18:24,201
-Mom, stop it.
-No, I'm serious.

409
00:18:24,237 --> 00:18:28,237
I raised you both to be strong
and independent, and you are.

410
00:18:28,275 --> 00:18:32,705
So whatever you decide,
I'll support.

411
00:18:35,282 --> 00:18:37,422
Let's do it.

412
00:18:37,450 --> 00:18:39,790
Go ahead.
Chop us in half.

413
00:18:39,819 --> 00:18:41,789
-[ Chuckles ]
-Katie?

414
00:18:41,821 --> 00:18:43,461
We obviously need
both your consent.

415
00:18:43,490 --> 00:18:45,730
-Okay.
-You sure?

416
00:18:45,758 --> 00:18:47,758
You want to talk more?
Have any questions?

417
00:18:47,794 --> 00:18:51,364
No. I'm good.
Let's do it.

418
00:18:54,901 --> 00:18:56,571
Shaun: I want a car.

419
00:18:56,603 --> 00:18:57,803
So get one.

420
00:18:57,837 --> 00:18:58,967
You've been driving
a half-hour,

421
00:18:59,005 --> 00:19:01,565
and you're already better than
half the people in San Jose.

422
00:19:01,608 --> 00:19:04,508
I get distracted
when I'm alone.

423
00:19:04,544 --> 00:19:06,654
That's why I miss my bus
sometimes.

424
00:19:06,679 --> 00:19:10,279
Dr. Glassman thinks
I'd do the same thing driving.

425
00:19:10,317 --> 00:19:12,487
He's probably right.

426
00:19:14,554 --> 00:19:15,864
Want to have some fun?

427
00:19:15,888 --> 00:19:18,658
-I'm already having fun.
-Stop the car.

428
00:19:18,691 --> 00:19:20,291
-Why?
-Just do it.

429
00:19:20,327 --> 00:19:23,197
[ Tires screech ]

430
00:19:23,230 --> 00:19:24,300
Thank you.

431
00:19:24,331 --> 00:19:27,831
Don't worry. We're the only car
on the road right now.

432
00:19:27,867 --> 00:19:29,897
Put your left foot
on the brake.

433
00:19:29,936 --> 00:19:31,766
Mm, okay.

434
00:19:31,804 --> 00:19:33,314
There we go.

435
00:19:33,340 --> 00:19:36,240
Now hold it all the way down.
There you go.

436
00:19:36,276 --> 00:19:39,876
Okay, now floor the gas
with your right foot.

437
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:42,350
[ Engine revs ]

438
00:19:42,382 --> 00:19:44,682
I-I don't know about this.

439
00:19:44,717 --> 00:19:45,987
No, it's okay.
It's okay.

440
00:19:46,018 --> 00:19:49,788
Now slowly ease your left foot
off the brake...

441
00:19:50,890 --> 00:19:52,790
...until you hear...

442
00:19:52,825 --> 00:19:54,585
[ Tires squealing ]
...this.

443
00:19:54,627 --> 00:19:56,527
I smell smoke.

444
00:19:56,563 --> 00:19:58,333
Yeah,
that's the point, Shaun.

445
00:19:58,365 --> 00:20:01,265
It's burning rubber.
Do it again.

446
00:20:02,802 --> 00:20:03,942
-Okay.
-[ Chuckles ]

447
00:20:04,637 --> 00:20:07,437
[ Engine revving,
tires squealing ]

448
00:20:10,443 --> 00:20:11,883
Now, this is fun.

449
00:20:11,911 --> 00:20:13,981
[ Engine revving,
tires squealing ]

450
00:20:14,013 --> 00:20:15,383
Okay, that's enough.

451
00:20:15,415 --> 00:20:17,445
We need some rubber left
to get us home.

452
00:20:17,484 --> 00:20:19,894
I am burning rubber.

453
00:20:19,919 --> 00:20:21,719
Okay, Shaun,
it's time to stop.
Okay.

454
00:20:23,656 --> 00:20:25,686
Shaun, take your other foot
off the gas!

455
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:27,525
Shaun, look out!

456
00:20:28,461 --> 00:20:30,561
It's the other foot!
Other foot!

457
00:20:30,597 --> 00:20:31,727
It's the other foot!
It's the other foot!

458
00:20:31,764 --> 00:20:33,374
It's the other foot!

459
00:20:35,802 --> 00:20:37,942
Dr. Ko and I
have been working for months

460
00:20:37,970 --> 00:20:39,770
to map the structure
of Jenny and Katie's brain.
Mm-hmm.

461
00:20:39,806 --> 00:20:41,536
-Don't you mean "brains"?
-Actually,

462
00:20:41,574 --> 00:20:43,784
while different regions operate
independently for each sister,

463
00:20:43,810 --> 00:20:45,450
there is
a single brain mass.

464
00:20:45,478 --> 00:20:47,448
That's why all their
previous neurosurgeons

465
00:20:47,480 --> 00:20:49,020
insisted separation
was impossible.

466
00:20:49,048 --> 00:20:51,618
The real problem won't be
dividing their brains

467
00:20:51,651 --> 00:20:53,751
but dividing their veins.

468
00:20:53,786 --> 00:20:56,716
They share a single
sagittal sinus vein.

469
00:20:56,756 --> 00:20:58,386
Melendez:
Which we'll give to Jenny.

470
00:20:58,425 --> 00:21:00,585
Then we'll create
a new one for Katie

471
00:21:00,627 --> 00:21:02,057
using a grafted vein
from her leg.

472
00:21:02,094 --> 00:21:04,704
Nice. You've gotten them
up to speed fast.

473
00:21:04,731 --> 00:21:06,931
Well, with 6 months of prep
to do in 12 hours,

474
00:21:06,966 --> 00:21:08,396
it was their only choice.

475
00:21:08,435 --> 00:21:10,035
So, let's get started.

476
00:21:10,069 --> 00:21:11,339
-I crashed.
-We didn't.

477
00:21:11,371 --> 00:21:12,541
We just --
-Yes, I-I crashed.

478
00:21:12,572 --> 00:21:14,042
I hit something.
-Shaun. Shaun.

479
00:21:14,073 --> 00:21:15,943
I hit something.
I did. I hit something.

480
00:21:15,975 --> 00:21:16,975
-Shaun, you --
-I know I did.

481
00:21:17,009 --> 00:21:18,749
-I felt it. I crashed.
-Shaun, you didn't crash.

482
00:21:18,778 --> 00:21:19,908
-Yes.
-You just drove off the road...

483
00:21:19,946 --> 00:21:20,876
-No.
-...and it was totally my fault.

484
00:21:20,913 --> 00:21:22,523
No, you're wrong.
Nuh-unh. I hit something.

485
00:21:22,549 --> 00:21:23,349
-No, you didn't.
-I felt it.

486
00:21:23,383 --> 00:21:24,083
I crashed.
-No, Shaun, look at me.

487
00:21:24,116 --> 00:21:24,916
-I crashed.
-Calm down. Calm.

488
00:21:24,951 --> 00:21:27,691
-Okay. Okay.
-Look at me. Look at me.

489
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:28,920
Breathe.

490
00:21:28,955 --> 00:21:32,325
Whatever happened, whatever
you felt, you did nothing wrong.

491
00:21:32,359 --> 00:21:34,929
It was all my fault,
okay?

492
00:21:34,961 --> 00:21:37,901
[ Breathing deeply ]

493
00:21:37,930 --> 00:21:41,500
Okay. Dr. Glassman --
He was right.

494
00:21:41,534 --> 00:21:44,804
I-I should not be allowed
to drive.

495
00:21:44,837 --> 00:21:46,837
No, no.

496
00:21:46,873 --> 00:21:49,513
[ Sighs ]

497
00:21:51,077 --> 00:21:51,907
Shaun.

498
00:21:51,944 --> 00:21:55,014
No, I'm not going to drive,
thank you.

499
00:21:55,047 --> 00:21:57,877
Yeah, I -- I know.
No one is.

500
00:21:57,917 --> 00:22:00,517
'Cause you were right.
We did hit something.

501
00:22:00,553 --> 00:22:06,063
**

502
00:22:06,092 --> 00:22:11,802
**

503
00:22:11,831 --> 00:22:14,471
[ Monitor beeping ]

504
00:22:16,002 --> 00:22:17,602
Everything
is still looking good.

505
